name: CallMatcher
comment: A mock/mock.CallMatcher is a special matcher used to match method calls (i.e. a method name and set of arguments). It is not a mock/mock.Matcher like the unit test mock/mock.Matcher, but instead represents a method name and a collection of mock/mock.Matchers, one per argument, that will be applied to the parameters to decide if the method call is a match.

constructors.comment: Constructor for mock/mock.CallMatcher. mock/mock.CallMatcher.CallMatcher-.name can be null to match anything, or a literal dart-core.String, a predicate dart-core.Function, or a mock/mock.Matcher. The various arguments can be scalar values or mock/mock.Matchers.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: We keep our behavior specifications in a Map, which is keyed by the mock/mock.CallMatcher. To make the keys unique and to get a descriptive value for the mock/mock.CallMatcher we have this override of toString().

matches.name: matches
matches.comment: Given a mock/mock.CallMatcher.matches.method name and list of mock/mock.CallMatcher.matches.arguments, return true if it matches this [CallMatcher.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides mock/mock.CallMatcher.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and mock/mock.CallMatcher.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the mock/mock.CallMatcher.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
mock/mock.CallMatcher.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to mock/mock.CallMatcher.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If mock/mock.CallMatcher.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of mock/mock.CallMatcher.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.
